 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'jasonpang', 'comment_id': 234044993.0, 'datetime': '2016-07-20 18:50:40+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "can occur:

Technically, why it occurs: When our service worker receives a push event, it has to fetch the actual notification from OneSignal's servers, since we have (at this time) not yet implemented the new web push payload protocol. If we successfully fetch a notification, we display it. Otherwise this error occurs if we can't display a backup notification.

- No messages to fetch from OneSignal
  - (Potential issue) If notifications are queued slower than they are sent, clients will not have any messages to retrieve when they get the push signal.
- A third-party service worker is running, which will still receive the push event, but will not know what to do. This is a likely case described in the second comment of this thread.
- An IndexedDB error occurs `(ServiceWorker.js:693 DOMException: Failed to execute 'transaction' on 'IDBDatabase': The database connection is closing.(‚Ä¶))` which prevents our service worker from being able to retrieve the necessary settings so the method fails, no notification is displayed, and they get this message
- Internet connection fails when the notification is being retrieved, or possibly some ultra power saving  modes on some devices will let the GCM signal through, but Chrome won't be able to make normal network requests to our server to retrieve the notification due to the ultra power saving mode", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'aumouth', 'comment_id': 296989321.0, 'datetime': '2017-04-25 10:31:33+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_3', 'text': 'I have this issue ("This site has been upgraded in the backgrou..") too.

